and Re- Presentation: Language, Content, and the Reconstruction of Experience -- t15. G. H. Mead’s Understanding of the Nature of Speech in the Light of Contemporary Research -- tContributors -- tIndex -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGeorge Herbert Mead is widely considered one of the most influential American philosophers of the twentieth century, and his work remains vibrant and relevant to many areas of scholarly inquiry today. The Timeliness of George Herbert Mead brings together a range of scholars who provide detailed analyses of Mead’s importance to innovative fields of scholarship, including cognitive science, environmental studies, democratic epistemology, and social ethics, non-teleological historiography, and the history of the natural and social sciences. Edited by well-respected Mead scholars Hans Joas and Daniel R. Huebner, the volume as a whole makes a coherent statement that places Mead in dialogue with current research, pushing these domains of scholarship forward while also revitalizing the growing literature on an author who has an ongoing and major influence on sociology, psychology, and philosophy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aPragmatism. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aGeorge Herbert Mead.  acognitive science.  ademocracy.  aenvironmental studies.  ahistoriography.  ahistory.  aphilosophy.  apragmatism.  apsychology.  asociology.1 aBooth, Kelvin Jay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrewster, Bradley H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCamic, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCefaï, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaniel, Jos